
[1]pulley

   PULL'EY, n. plu. pulleys. [L. polus; Gr. to turn.]

   A small wheel turning on a pin in a block, with a furrow or groove in
   which runs the rope that turns it.

   The pulley is one of the mechanical powers. The word is used also in
   the general sense of tackle, to denote all parts of the machine for
   raising weights, of which the pulley forms a part.
